class Solution:
    def validPalindrome(self, s: str) -> bool:
        def is_palindrome_range(i, j):
            return all(s[k] == s[j-k+i] for k in range(i, j))

        left, right = 0, len(s) - 1
        while left < right:
            if s[left] != s[right]:
                # Try skipping either the left or the right character
                return is_palindrome_range(left + 1, right) or is_palindrome_range(left, right - 1)
            left, right = left + 1, right - 1
        return True
```

This solution checks if the string `s` can be a palindrome by allowing the deletion of at most one character. It uses a helper function `is_palindrome_range` to check if a substring is a palindrome. The main loop compares characters from the start and end of the string, moving towards the center. If a mismatch is found, it checks if skipping either the left or right character results in a palindrome.
